column1: What will be China's year-on-year GDP growth rate for the second quarter of 2022?
column5: ['Less than 4.0%', 'Between 4.0% and 5.0%, inclusive', 'More than 5.0% but less than 6.0%', 'Between 6.0% and 7.0%, inclusive', 'More than 7.0%']
column6: ['Economic Indicators']

Reaffirming my forecast. The economy took a huge hit because of Zero-Covid, but China did inject a massive amount of stimulus into the economy, so I think there is still a small chance that the answer for this question hits 4% or higher.

The Chinese economy expanded 4.8% YoY in Q1 of 2022, above the market consensus of 4.4% and faster than a 4.0% growth in the previous period. However, the risk of a sharp slowdown in the coming months heightened, amid widespread COVID-19 lockdowns, a prolonged downturn in the property sector, and uncertainty from the war in Ukraine. Meantime, separate data on March activity showed retail sales fell 3.5% YoY, down for the 1st time since July 2020, and worse than market expectations. Analysts say that April data will likely weaken further, dragged down by strict restrictions in the financial hub of Shanghai.

"The global context will also weigh on China's outlook in 2022, by sharply reducing export growth and dampening confidence amid heightened geopolitical tensions. This is expected to exacerbate the slowdown caused by recurrent COVID-19 outbreaks in some places and related lockdowns in parts of China which have disrupted supply chains and significantly weakened household and business activity. Following a strong 8.1 percent rebound in 2021, the World Bank expects China's growth to slow to 4.3 percent this year. This rate of growth is below the economy's potential－the sustainable growth rate of output at full capacity.Our forecast reflects the sharp deceleration in activity in the second quarter of 2022 that took place despite policy actions to cushion the economic slowdown. With the easing of pandemic controls in Shanghai and Beijing, and barring any major COVID-19 outbreaks, growth momentum is expected to rebound in the second half of 2022, helped also by additional policy stimulus announced by the State Council, China's Cabinet, last month. "

Q1 2022 growth was 4.8% From March 2022, spending for private consumption and investment in durable goods fell dramatically. With the current COVID outbreak dragging on in critical regions at high pace, the financial & economic fallout will continue to make higher growth rates than 5.0% unattainable whatever catch-up initiatives by the government or pent-up demand could add over the next eight weeks - despite rumors that Shaghai is perhaps going to lift its stric lockdown shortly to avoid more damage to the economy despite zero-COVID-strategy.

Just missed this: https://money.usnews.com/investing/news/articles/2022-04-16/china-data-to-show-sharp-march-deterioration-as-covid-bites-but-solid-first-quarter-growth "Barclays estimates that the second-quarter GDP growth could dip to 3%, dragging 2022 growth to 4.2%, if Shanghai's extended lockdown were to last for one month and partial lockdowns in the rest of the country remained in place for two months." Yes, this seems highly likely to me at this point. I have to leave open the possibility that 1) Zero covid policy ends sometime soon or 2) China finds some way to artificially juice the numbers either through stimulus/monetary policy or directly fudging the numbers. But ultimately it's hard to hide the effects of locking down a hundred million plus people, and it seems like giving up on zero covid because you were too inept to pull it off is too embarrassing to permit

What I do know is that Shanghai is something like 4% of total China GDP and 10% of international trade and may be under fairly strict lockdown for maybe half of the quarter or more. Cases are still going up country wide so we can expect lockdowns and restrictions to spread throughout the country. Q1 2020 GDP had a massive retraction, but also shutdowns I think were harsher at the time (how did they differ specifically? I don't currently know).

I think the China housing market crash could significantly hurt their economy in 2022, and the zero-covid policy will also put a major damper on growth if they don't switch to a new policy that accepts a certain level of endemicity. A great article came out today about the China housing market that is worth reading: https://fortune.com/2021/11/09/china-economy-growth-outlook-real-estate-crash/

There are a lot of downward pressures on the economy and so I think there will be growth but at a more muted pace than in recent times. Maintaining a zero-COVID policy will also likely cost, in terms of supressing growth.

1) China spent too many years inflating their GDP growth rate, so they'll use the opportunity to help the reality catch back up with the numbers. 2) It's not in their political interest to look like their economy is robust right now (too much wolf-warrior backlash). 3) El Nino makes China colder than normal, so they'll preserve energy supplies for heat. 4) With their property bubble popping, there will be a LOT of idle cement production, steel production, and construction.
I'm guessing it'll be around 6; but hopefully on the higher side :)
